COVID-19 Is Cutting Into Vital Money U.S. Migrant Workers Send Back HomeEnlarge this image toggle caption Moises Castillo/AP Moises Castillo/APAs U.S. joblessness climbs, immigrant workers are facing a tough decision: pay rent and buy food or send critical dollars to family back home.
Anabel usually sends money every two weeks to El Salvador where she supports her two adult children and three grandchildren.
He estimates that remittances to Latin America will fall this year by at least 7%, similar to the decline seen during the 2009 global recession.
The drop in dollars sent home by workers in the U.S. comes as Latin America faces its worst recession in 50 years.
For now, Ari, 33, a nanny in D.C., is still able to send money to her aging parents in Oaxaca, Mexico.